<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F330FFFEFF15FD99FC1166A5" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F330FFFEFF15FD99FC1166A5" blockId="9.[192,1440,544,666]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFF15FD99FED66607" bold="true" box="[192,335,544,568]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
This species appears to be most closely related to 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFC61FD99FBEA6607" authority="Flowers, 2018" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" box="[948,1139,544,568]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ledesmae" status="n. sp.">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFC61FD99FBEA6607" box="[948,1139,544,568]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Beltia ledesmae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A38257CBF330FFFEFBAEFD99FB276608" box="[1147,1214,544,567]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" rank="species">n. sp.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, but can be distinguished by its smaller size and less curved lateral margins of the pronotum. It differs from other small metallic green 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFEA0FDD8FE276646" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1881" box="[373,446,609,633]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFEA0FDD8FE276646" box="[373,446,609,633]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Beltia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(e.g. 
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFE2AFDDBFBB16646" box="[511,1064,609,633]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFE2AFDDBFD196646" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" box="[511,640,609,633]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="confusa">B. confusa</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFD59FDDBFC9D6646" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" box="[652,772,609,633]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="herreri">B. herreri</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFCDAFDDBFC346646" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" box="[783,941,609,633]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanchezae">B. sanchezae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFC6CFDDBFBB16646" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" box="[953,1064,609,633]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="talaga">B. talaga</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
) in having the pronotal lateral margins straighter and the apical angles more prominent.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C2DF6529F330FFFEFF15FD0AFBF16711" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8A7A36A2F330FFFEFF15FD0AFBF16711" blockId="9.[192,1441,691,814]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFF15FD0AFEDA66F4" bold="true" box="[192,323,691,715]" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Remarks.</emphasis>
Both 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFE5EFD0DFD8966F4" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" box="[395,528,692,715]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="awapita">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFE5EFD0DFD8966F4" box="[395,528,692,715]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">B. awapita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFD9FFD0DFD4366F4" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" box="[586,730,691,715]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ledesmae">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFD9FFD0DFD4366F4" box="[586,730,691,715]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">B. ledesmae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a large twisted subapical sclerite in the endophallus, unlike any other known species of 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFD81FD6DFD0566D3" authorityName="Jacoby" authorityYear="1881" box="[596,668,724,748]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFD81FD6DFD0566D3" box="[596,668,724,748]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Beltia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Their genitalia differ somewhat in the size of the spicule patches of the endophalli, and in the lack of a distinct crease on the side of the median lobe in 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFB6EFD4CFAD36733" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" box="[1211,1354,756,780]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ledesmae">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFB6EFD4CFAD36733" box="[1211,1354,756,780]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">B. ledesmae</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. 
<taxonomicName id="4DC54D21F330FFFEFA82FD4DFEBD6712" authorityName="Flowers" authorityYear="2018" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Beltia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="9" pageNumber="8" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="awapita">
<emphasis id="B8B1EAB0F330FFFEFA82FD4DFEBD6712" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Beltia awapita</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known from a single specimen in northwestern 
<collectingCountry id="F2D27632F330FFFEFC58FCAFFC6A6711" box="[909,1011,790,814]" name="Ecuador" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Ecuador</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation id="12FE2A27F330FFFEFBD6FCAFFBC26711" box="[1027,1115,790,814]" captionStart="Figures 78–79" captionStartId="43.[191,286,1850,1872]" captionTargetBox="[192,1441,412,1699]" captionTargetId="figure@43.[189,1443,412,1702]" captionTargetPageId="43" captionText="Figures 78–79. Distribution maps for Beltia spp. 78) Northwestern South America: B. confusa (star), B. gorgona (inverted triangles), B. placidula (blue circles), B. rugosa (red circle), B. weyrauchi (square). 79) Ecuador: B. awapita (hexagon), B. ledesmae (squares), B. napoensis (triangles), B. talaga (circle), B. tsachila (star)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3713527" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3713527/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="8">Fig. 79</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
